  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Verbs of Imminence (أفعال المقاربة)",
      "titleArabic": "أفعال المقاربة",
      "content": [
        "Verbs of imminence (أفعال المقاربة) indicate that an action is about to happen or is near to occurring.",
        "The most common is كَادَ (almost, nearly). They work like كَانَ, taking a subject (nominative) and a predicate."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "كَادَ - almost, nearly (كاد يسقط - he almost fell)",
        "أَوْشَكَ - is about to (أوشك أن يصل - he is about to arrive)",
        "كَرَبَ - is near to (rarely used)",
        "The predicate is usually a present tense verb with أَنْ"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "كَادَ الْوَلَدُ يَسْقُطُ", "english": "The boy almost fell" },
        { "arabic": "أَوْشَكَ الْمَطَرُ أَنْ يَنْزِلَ", "english": "The rain is about to fall" },
        { "arabic": "كَادَ الشَّمْسُ تَغْرُبُ", "english": "The sun is about to set" },
        { "arabic": "أَوْشَكْتُ أَنْ أَنْسَى", "english": "I almost forgot" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Usage Patterns of كاد",
      "titleArabic": "أنماط استخدام كاد",
      "content": [
        "كَادَ can be used with or without أَنْ before the predicate verb.",
        "Without أَنْ is more common in classical Arabic; with أَنْ is also acceptable."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "كَادَ يَفْعَلُ (without أَنْ) - more classical",
        "كَادَ أَنْ يَفْعَلَ (with أَنْ) - also correct",
        "With negation: لَمْ يَكَدْ - hardly, scarcely",
        "مَا كَادَ حَتَّى - no sooner... than"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "كَادَ يَمُوتُ مِنَ الْجُوعِ", "english": "He almost died of hunger" },
        { "arabic": "كَادَ أَنْ يَبْكِيَ", "english": "He was about to cry" },
        { "arabic": "لَمْ أَكَدْ أَفْهَمُ", "english": "I hardly understood" },
        { "arabic": "مَا كَادَ يَصِلُ حَتَّى نَامَ", "english": "No sooner did he arrive than he slept" }
      ]
    }
  ],
